イラストには、一人の少女と一台のオフロードバイクが描かれています。少女はバイクの前に立ち、無言の存在感を漂わせています。

彼女は黒を基調とした学生服風の衣装を着ており、胸元には赤いスカーフが鮮やかに結ばれています。外側には大きめのジャケットを羽織り、軍靴のような無骨なブーツを履いています。膝には包帯が巻かれ、戦いや旅の跡を思わせます。

顔には防毒マスクを装着しており、赤く光る瞳が露わになっていて、少し不穏な雰囲気を漂わせています。背中には刀を背負い、手には長物の武器を握っています。その先には黒いウサギのぬいぐるみ型キーホルダーがぶら下がっており、過酷な世界観の中でどこか幼さや哀愁を感じさせるアクセントとなっています。

少女の隣には錆びや傷が目立つオフロードバイクがあり、泥や埃をかぶりながらも力強く存在感を放っています。分厚いタイヤは険しい道を走り抜けてきたことを物語り、彼女の旅や戦いの相棒であることがうかがえます。

全体としてこのイラストは、廃墟や荒廃した世界を生き抜く戦士のような少女と、その相棒であるバイクを描いており、過酷さの中に孤独や強さ、そしてほんの少しの可愛らしさを同時に感じさせる雰囲気を持っています。

images.alt: In 2217, Orin Shaw, an unhoused man with an old non-surveillant CoreTag, becomes the compatible host for the Afterglow, a centuries-accumulated lattice of discarded simulations that quietly rides public sleep-pod nanoseeds. Each night adds “rings” to his body, making him faster, stronger, and perceptually sharper, while an ethical lock prevents lethal escalation and a built-in overlay lets him purge or halt the process at any time. Forced into a visible survival state, he first saves a child during a scaffold failure, then exposes “Gratitude Harvesters” staging disasters to farm social credit, disabling their jammer and redirecting a collapsing loader with nonlethal precision. Rejecting recruitment and celebrity, he files as SOURCE OPT-OUT: Defensive Only and chooses Partial Retention, freezing his enhancements at a deliberate level. He keeps using pods for rest but no longer grows, intervening rarely and precisely while the city’s humane, non-coercive systems leave him alone. Somewhere in forgotten caches, the Afterglow persists, patient, available to complete itself again if another corridor opens.

external.description: This week, we are joined by ⁠Jamie Levy⁠, Director of Adversary Tactics at ⁠Huntress⁠, who is discussing their work on "Active Exploitation of SonicWall VPNs." Huntress has released an urgent threat advisory on active exploitation of SonicWall VPNs, with attackers bypassing MFA, pivoting to domain controllers, and ultimately deploying Akira ransomware. The campaigns involve techniques such as disabling defenses, clearing logs, credential theft, and Bring Your Own Vulnerable Driver (BYOVD) attacks with legitimate Windows drivers. Organizations using SonicWall devices are strongly advised to disable SSL VPN access or restrict it via IP allow-listing, rotate credentials, and hunt for indicators of compromise as this remains an ongoing and evolving threat.
